reviews.review_text:
The Dead Played Well To Here To hear was well-received by the Copps crowd -- a good venue for the GD.

a pleasant show throughout -- nothing spectacular -- one you could amp up during a gathering of Dead Head friends and not be ashamed that they would not enjoy the ambience that this show, or you, could provide.

Indeed, this is such a handsome recording/remastering no one could expend their last sheer moments of delight on earth and not admit that this wouldn't have been due, adequate.

well-organized and competent playing -- some of Bruce's last stuff with the band and sweetly augmented by Mr. Get Along With Everybody "Wince" Velnick.

All of it is good, but it is rather short. Nice, though, now you can squeeze another show in tonight.

This show is reasonably well-executed and well-recorded. It deserves a 5 star rating more than a 4 star.

Call me jaded, call me insane, but to me, the GD usually afforded a 5 star rating -- not necessarily because of great performances or great recordings -- but because they turned on their love lights most every night.

In my hot so numble opinion.

The Other One  7:15 Check this out...
7 minutes into the Other One...
Crazy tightness....great recording...

As Well To Count the Angels.... The DS is fairly respectable.  The "space", listened through a good audio system is remarkably directional.  Take the 2 channel and filter through a 5.1 set-up.

Pretty damned sweet.

P.S. They actually sing "In a circle" after the first verse of The Other One which hadn't been sung since... Oh, I don't know... '68 or so ? *Astonishing* !

The Other One! The Dark Star is nice, nothing remarkable except at the end they jam on the "You and I while we can" chord progression... unusual.

The Other One is the real treat for me. It starts out of the spaceyness and the drummers kick it right at the chorus, which give it extra heaviness. Healy does the chimpmunk thing on Bob and it sounds cool. The jamming wild post first verse... check it out!

Totally biased Was at this show and rank it as my best. Maybe it's only a mediocre show but having the Dead return to my backyard and being treated to my one and only Dark Star... that says it all. The set II opener of Shakedown, Women, DS made for a memorable night.Other One and Maggie's Farm were other highlights

20th Anniversary Seems like a lifetime ago, and like yesterday at the same time. Myself and three friends from high school (in college at the time) met up for the trek. Ironically, I saw one of my traveling companions just yesterday (20 years after the show), and reminded him of the adventure.

I can't believe that I'll say this, but the drums/space was probably the most enjoyable D/S that I ever saw, or ever heard. It might have been the influences, but it still sounded good to here again.

The matrix is awesome, and it has the BEW, that the SBD is somehow missing.

Great memories with this one. Can't give a 5-star, but I'll give it 4.

27th Trip Around the Sun While the first set is good, the real magic arrives in the second. 13-minute Shakedown is followed by a 10-minute Man Smart Women Smarter that makes its way into Dark Star. From there, we're treated to an absolutely masterful hour of music. After making its way through drums and space, the Other One - as doug_the_dude aptly puts it - "rips the lid off." It segues into the first SOTM of 92 (last played 19 shows prior on 12/28/91). I almost want to give the show five stars on the beauty of the hour suite alone. But, I don't know, I'm with mush72 and going with four. 

Althea is featured on the 30 trips definitive live story. This is Bruce's fourth to last show as a member of the Grateful Dead.
Phenomenal The setlist is mind blowing, the playing is excellent, and Hunter's sound is just great.
